<section class="hero">
  <h1>Take your group chat<br />to Eleven.</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Eleven is a group-chat and messaging app, just like the ones you're used
    to — groups, photos, reactions, replies, bots — without the tracking and
    metrics of big tech.
  </p>
  <div class="cta">
    <a class="btn btn-primary" href="#get">Get Eleven</a>
    <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/security/">How it stays private</a>
  </div>
  <p class="fine">
    Invite-only — there's no public sign-up. Someone already in a chat sends you
    a link.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="pains" aria-label="Why Eleven exists">
  <h2>Ever wondered&hellip;</h2>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why is chatting to your friends run by big tech?</h3>
    <p>
      A group chat with your actual friends doesn't need a social network
      wrapped around it. It doesn't need an algorithm deciding what you see,
      and it definitely doesn't need a business model that runs on knowing
      who you talk to.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why do you need a mobile number to talk to people you already know?</h3>
    <p>
      Your phone number is an identity you hand over before you've even said
      hello. Eleven skips accounts entirely — you join with a secret link
      from someone already inside.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why choose between owning your chat and actually enjoying it?</h3>
    <p>
      You don't need to self-host Eleven, but if you do, it's designed to be
      as simple as possible. Push notifications just work via a shared relay,
      and keys can be backed up on our shared secure home server — both
      optional.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="attrs" aria-label="What Eleven is">
  <h2>Eleven is&hellip;</h2>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Familiar and easy</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        You shouldn't have to learn how Eleven works. Click a link and
        you're chatting. Saving your chats so you never lose them is one
        more click &mdash; no sign-up, no account, nothing to remember.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Open</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Eleven isn't run by a corporation or a big organisation. If someone
        invites you to a space, you're in &mdash; and the code that runs it
        is out in the open for anyone to check.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Secure</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Too many apps end up &ldquo;not secure&rdquo;. Eleven is built to be
        secure enough: if the server were hacked, there'd be nothing on it
        to expose. Private chats are secret to the two people in them; group
        chats are secret to the group. That's it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Web-based</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Eleven keeps your messages on a server on the web, so you can pick
        up any device and carry on. A browser window? Check. An installable
        app with push notifications? Check. Eleven doesn't shy away from
        being a web app.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Native</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        For all that, Eleven is native where it counts &mdash; in the feel.
        On iOS and Mac the apps are quick to download, fast to use, and easy
        on your battery and your memory.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Tracking-free</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        No trackers. None at all. Anything that could personally identify
        you stays secret. That's it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>AI-enabled</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Every attribute above is a reason big tech never built this: there's
        no one left to monetise. AI changes the maths &mdash; it makes a
        product this considered, with this much respect for the person using
        it, possible at a fraction of the cost.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's built with the latest AI models &mdash; and audited by them too,
        including a security review by Claude&nbsp;Fable. Eleven is in beta
        with the source open, so you don't have to take our word for any of
        it: check the code yourself.
      </p>
      <p>
        And if you want them, AI agents can join your chats to do genuinely
        useful &mdash; or genuinely strange &mdash; things. You choose how
        much: an assistant in one group, a quiet bot in another, or none at
        all. Nothing is on by default.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="creed" aria-label="What Eleven proves">
  <p>
    <span class="creed-lead">Eleven is proof</span> that great experience,
    good-enough security, openness, and treating people as people &mdash; not
    eyeballs to be monetised &mdash; can all live in one app.
  </p>
</section>

